<h1>Problem 1958 - 2023 IMOSL, G6, G</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 8</h2>
<p>Let \(ABC\) be an acute-angled triangle with circumcircle \(\omega\). A circle \(\Gamma\) is internally tangent to \(\omega\) at \(A\) and also tangent to \(BC\) at \(D\). Let \(AB\) and \(AC\) intersect \(\Gamma\) at \(P\) and \(Q\) respectively. Let \(M\) and \(N\) be points on line \(BC\) such that \(B\) is the midpoint of \(DM\) and \(C\) is the midpoint of \(DN\). Lines \(MP\) and \(NQ\) meet at \(K\) and intersect \(\Gamma\) again at \(I\) and \(J\) respectively. The ray \(KA\) meets the circumcircle of triangle \(IJK\) at \(X\ne K\).<br><br> Prove that \(\angle BXP  =\angle CXQ\).</p>
